[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":761},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F":737,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F":746},"\u002Fgit\u002F20260226\u002F799954596\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":721,"date":722,"description":723,"extension":724,"lang":725,"meta":726,"navigation":474,"path":727,"readingMinutes":728,"seo":729,"standalone":730,"stem":731,"tags":732,"tldr":734,"updated":722,"url":735,"__hash__":736},"content\u002Fen\u002FGit\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force.md","A Safer Alternative to git push --force: git push --force-with-lease","5460995799",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":710},"minimark",[11,19,24,40,46,49,55,58,88,91,108,111,160,177,181,200,206,214,229,235,317,333,338,355,368,375,393,410,414,422,443,446,519,523,529,532,552,555,576,579,595,599,671,674,703,706],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"git push --force-with-lease","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fgit\u002Fgit-push\u002FGemini_Generated_Image_vtds81vtds81vtds_1280x698.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26,27,31,32,35,36,39],{},"In daily dev work, we constantly use ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"git rebase"," or ",[28,33,34],{},"git commit --amend"," to clean up commit history. The problem: these rewrite commits that have already been pushed, so your local history diverges from the remote — and a normal ",[28,37,38],{},"git push"," gets rejected. You have to force-push.",[12,41,42,43,45],{},"So this post is about ",[28,44,17],{},", a safer way to force-push. It checks the remote hasn't moved before letting you force-push.",[20,47,38],{"id":48},"git-push",[12,50,51,52,54],{},"You're probably already pretty familiar with ",[28,53,38],{}," — push your local changes to the remote (GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, whatever) so your team can see them.",[12,56,57],{},"Most people know these forms:",[59,60,61,67,73,82],"ul",{},[62,63,64,66],"li",{},[28,65,38],{},": push the current branch to the remote.",[62,68,69,72],{},[28,70,71],{},"git push origin \u003Cbranch>",": push a specific branch to the remote.",[62,74,75,78,79,81],{},[28,76,77],{},"git push -u origin \u003Cbranch>",": push and set the upstream so future ",[28,80,38],{}," calls don't need the branch name.",[62,83,84,87],{},[28,85,86],{},"git push --force",": force-push, overwriting the remote (today's main character).",[12,89,90],{},"But there are advanced uses too, like:",[59,92,93,102],{},[62,94,95,31,98,101],{},[28,96,97],{},"git push --all",[28,99,100],{},"git push --branches",": push all branches to the remote.",[62,103,104,107],{},[28,105,106],{},"git push --tags",": push all tags to the remote.",[12,109,110],{},"You can also do:",[112,113,118],"pre",{"className":114,"code":115,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","# Delete a remote branch\ngit push origin :\u003Cbranch>\n","bash","",[28,119,120,129],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,122,125],"span",{"class":123,"line":124},"line",1,[121,126,128],{"class":127},"sQrFR","# Delete a remote branch\n",[121,130,132,136,140,143,146,150,153,157],{"class":123,"line":131},2,[121,133,135],{"class":134},"s_sBn","git",[121,137,139],{"class":138},"sTRMh"," push",[121,141,142],{"class":138}," origin",[121,144,145],{"class":138}," :",[121,147,149],{"class":148},"sWyjQ","\u003C",[121,151,152],{"class":138},"branc",[121,154,156],{"class":155},"sMAXC","h",[121,158,159],{"class":148},">\n",[12,161,162,163,165,166,168,169,176],{},"OK, those are some of the advanced ones. Today's focus is ",[28,164,86],{}," and ",[28,167,17],{},". For other options, see the ",[170,171,175],"a",{"href":172,"rel":173},"https:\u002F\u002Fgit-scm.com\u002Fdocs\u002Fgit-push\u002F",[174],"nofollow","Git official docs",".",[20,178,180],{"id":179},"git-push-force-git-push-force-with-lease","git push --force & git push --force-with-lease",[12,182,183,184,187,188,190,191,194,195,199],{},"This is probably the most evil usage. You can run ",[28,185,186],{},"git push -f",", ",[28,189,86],{},", or ",[28,192,193],{},"git push origin +\u003Cbranch>"," to ",[196,197,198],"strong",{},"force"," push your local changes to the remote, overwriting anything your teammates pushed (translation: making their day's work pointless).",[12,201,202,203,205],{},"That's why a lot of companies just ban ",[28,204,86],{}," outright.",[12,207,208,209,211,212,176],{},"But in practice you can't completely avoid it — sometimes you genuinely need to rewrite history (with ",[28,210,30],{},", for example), and you'll need to force-push. So Git provides a safer way: ",[28,213,17],{},[12,215,216,217,220,221,224,225,228],{},"Here's how it works: before force-pushing, Git compares the current remote branch tip with ",[196,218,219],{},"the remote-tracking branch your local has cached"," (like ",[28,222,223],{},"origin\u002Fmain","). If they match, that means nobody's pushed anything new since your last ",[28,226,227],{},"git fetch",", so the force-push goes through. If they don't match, someone pushed something in the meantime — Git rejects the push and saves you from overwriting their work.",[12,230,231,232,234],{},"When you use ",[28,233,17],{}," and someone else pushed after you, you'll see something like:",[112,236,238],{"className":114,"code":237,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"To \u003Cremote>\n ! [rejected]        \u003Cbranch> -> \u003Cbranch> (stale info)\nerror: failed to push some refs to '\u003Cremote>'\n",[28,239,240,256,292],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,241,242,245,248,251,254],{"class":123,"line":124},[121,243,244],{"class":134},"To",[121,246,247],{"class":148}," \u003C",[121,249,250],{"class":138},"remot",[121,252,253],{"class":155},"e",[121,255,159],{"class":148},[121,257,258,261,264,266,269,272,275,277,279,281,283,286,289],{"class":123,"line":131},[121,259,260],{"class":148}," !",[121,262,263],{"class":155}," [rejected]        ",[121,265,149],{"class":148},[121,267,268],{"class":134},"branch",[121,270,271],{"class":155},"> -",[121,273,274],{"class":148},">",[121,276,247],{"class":148},[121,278,152],{"class":138},[121,280,156],{"class":155},[121,282,274],{"class":148},[121,284,285],{"class":155}," (stale ",[121,287,288],{"class":138},"info",[121,290,291],{"class":155},")\n",[121,293,295,298,301,304,306,309,312,314],{"class":123,"line":294},3,[121,296,297],{"class":134},"error:",[121,299,300],{"class":138}," failed",[121,302,303],{"class":138}," to",[121,305,139],{"class":138},[121,307,308],{"class":138}," some",[121,310,311],{"class":138}," refs",[121,313,303],{"class":138},[121,315,316],{"class":138}," '\u003Cremote>'\n",[12,318,319,320,323,324,326,327,329,330,332],{},"The ",[28,321,322],{},"(stale info)"," means your locally cached remote state is out of date. You need to ",[28,325,227],{}," first to get the latest remote state, re-apply your changes (re-",[28,328,30],{},", for instance), and then ",[28,331,17],{}," again.",[334,335,337],"h3",{"id":336},"when-do-you-need-to-force-push","When do you need to force-push?",[12,339,340,341,343,344,347,348,350,351,354],{},"You might be thinking: \"If ",[28,342,38],{}," gets rejected, can't I just ",[28,345,346],{},"git pull"," first and then ",[28,349,38],{},"? Why bother with ",[28,352,353],{},"--force","?\"",[12,356,357,358,361,362,364,365,367],{},"Right — if your local history just ",[196,359,360],{},"diverges"," from the remote in a simple way (you and a teammate both committed to the same branch separately), then ",[28,363,346],{}," + ",[28,366,38],{}," is enough.",[12,369,370,371,374],{},"But when you've used ",[196,372,373],{},"history-rewriting"," operations, things change:",[59,376,377,382,387],{},[62,378,379,381],{},[28,380,30],{},": replays commits onto a new base",[62,383,384,386],{},[28,385,34],{},": modifies the last commit",[62,388,389,392],{},[28,390,391],{},"git reset"," followed by re-commits: rewrites history",[12,394,395,396,399,400,403,404,407,408,176],{},"These create new commit SHAs, so your local history is ",[196,397,398],{},"completely different"," from the remote — not just \"behind\" but \"diverged and unmergeable\", so you ",[196,401,402],{},"have to"," force-push. And in that case ",[28,405,406],{},"--force-with-lease"," is much safer than plain ",[28,409,353],{},[20,411,413],{"id":412},"a-known-pitfall-with-force-with-lease","A known pitfall with --force-with-lease",[12,415,416,418,419,421],{},[28,417,406],{}," is safer than ",[28,420,353],{}," but it's not foolproof.",[12,423,424,425,220,428,430,431,433,434,436,437,439,440],{},"Its protection compares your ",[196,426,427],{},"locally cached remote-tracking branch",[28,429,223],{},"), not the live remote. So if you ",[28,432,227],{}," (or ",[28,435,346],{},") before force-pushing, your local remote-tracking branch gets updated to the latest, and ",[28,438,406],{}," now thinks \"you already know about the latest remote state\" — and lets the force-push through. ",[196,441,442],{},"The protection is gone.",[12,444,445],{},"For example:",[112,447,449],{"className":114,"code":448,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"# You rebased and you're about to force-push\ngit rebase -i HEAD~3\n\n# Habit kicks in — you fetch first (this is what kills the protection!)\ngit fetch origin\n\n# Now --force-with-lease won't block you, even if the remote has new commits\ngit push --force-with-lease origin main\n",[28,450,451,456,470,476,482,493,498,504],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,452,453],{"class":123,"line":124},[121,454,455],{"class":127},"# You rebased and you're about to force-push\n",[121,457,458,460,463,467],{"class":123,"line":131},[121,459,135],{"class":134},[121,461,462],{"class":138}," rebase",[121,464,466],{"class":465},"sCcAr"," -i",[121,468,469],{"class":138}," HEAD~3\n",[121,471,472],{"class":123,"line":294},[121,473,475],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":474},true,"\n",[121,477,479],{"class":123,"line":478},4,[121,480,481],{"class":127},"# Habit kicks in — you fetch first (this is what kills the protection!)\n",[121,483,485,487,490],{"class":123,"line":484},5,[121,486,135],{"class":134},[121,488,489],{"class":138}," fetch",[121,491,492],{"class":138}," origin\n",[121,494,496],{"class":123,"line":495},6,[121,497,475],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":474},[121,499,501],{"class":123,"line":500},7,[121,502,503],{"class":127},"# Now --force-with-lease won't block you, even if the remote has new commits\n",[121,505,507,509,511,514,516],{"class":123,"line":506},8,[121,508,135],{"class":134},[121,510,139],{"class":138},[121,512,513],{"class":465}," --force-with-lease",[121,515,142],{"class":138},[121,517,518],{"class":138}," main\n",[334,520,522],{"id":521},"force-if-includes","--force-if-includes",[12,524,525,526,528],{},"Git 2.30+ adds ",[28,527,522],{}," to fix this pitfall. It adds an extra check: has the latest commit on the remote-tracking branch been integrated into your local branch? If you only fetched without actually merging the remote changes in, the push gets rejected.",[12,530,531],{},"Use them together:",[112,533,535],{"className":114,"code":534,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"git push --force-with-lease --force-if-includes origin main\n",[28,536,537],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,538,539,541,543,545,548,550],{"class":123,"line":124},[121,540,135],{"class":134},[121,542,139],{"class":138},[121,544,513],{"class":465},[121,546,547],{"class":465}," --force-if-includes",[121,549,142],{"class":138},[121,551,518],{"class":138},[12,553,554],{},"If that's too much to type every time, set up a Git alias:",[112,556,558],{"className":114,"code":557,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"git config --global alias.pushfl \"push --force-with-lease --force-if-includes\"\n",[28,559,560],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,561,562,564,567,570,573],{"class":123,"line":124},[121,563,135],{"class":134},[121,565,566],{"class":138}," config",[121,568,569],{"class":465}," --global",[121,571,572],{"class":138}," alias.pushfl",[121,574,575],{"class":138}," \"push --force-with-lease --force-if-includes\"\n",[12,577,578],{},"Then you can just:",[112,580,582],{"className":114,"code":581,"language":116,"meta":117,"style":117},"git pushfl origin main\n",[28,583,584],{"__ignoreMap":117},[121,585,586,588,591,593],{"class":123,"line":124},[121,587,135],{"class":134},[121,589,590],{"class":138}," pushfl",[121,592,142],{"class":138},[121,594,518],{"class":138},[20,596,598],{"id":597},"summary","Summary",[600,601,602,618],"table",{},[603,604,605],"thead",{},[606,607,608,612,615],"tr",{},[609,610,611],"th",{},"Command",[609,613,614],{},"Behavior",[609,616,617],{},"Safety",[619,620,621,634,646,659],"tbody",{},[606,622,623,628,631],{},[624,625,626],"td",{},[28,627,38],{},[624,629,630],{},"Only allows fast-forward updates",[624,632,633],{},"Safest",[606,635,636,640,643],{},[624,637,638],{},[28,639,17],{},[624,641,642],{},"Compares cached remote-tracking branch, allows force-push only if matched",[624,644,645],{},"Safe",[606,647,648,653,656],{},[624,649,650],{},[28,651,652],{},"git push --force-with-lease --force-if-includes",[624,654,655],{},"Additionally checks remote changes are integrated locally",[624,657,658],{},"Safer",[606,660,661,665,668],{},[624,662,663],{},[28,664,86],{},[624,666,667],{},"Unconditionally overwrites remote",[624,669,670],{},"Dangerous",[12,672,673],{},"In short:",[59,675,676,684,695],{},[62,677,678,683],{},[196,679,680,681],{},"Never use ",[28,682,86],{}," unless you're absolutely sure what you're doing.",[62,685,686,694],{},[196,687,688,689,691,692],{},"Use ",[28,690,17],{}," instead of ",[28,693,353],{}," — minimum safety baseline.",[62,696,697,702],{},[196,698,699,700],{},"Pair it with ",[28,701,522],{}," for the strongest protection.",[12,704,705],{},"Build the habit. Protect yourself and your teammates' work.",[707,708,709],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":117,"searchDepth":131,"depth":131,"links":711},[712,713,714,717,720],{"id":22,"depth":131,"text":23},{"id":48,"depth":131,"text":38},{"id":179,"depth":131,"text":180,"children":715},[716],{"id":336,"depth":294,"text":337},{"id":412,"depth":131,"text":413,"children":718},[719],{"id":521,"depth":294,"text":522},{"id":597,"depth":131,"text":598},"Git","2026-02-26 09:39:40","After using git rebase or git commit --amend to rewrite history, you have to force-push to update the remote. But git push --force overwrites the remote unconditionally — which can blow away your teammates' work. This post introduces a safer alternative: git push --force-with-lease and --force-if-includes, which add a layer of protection before you force-push.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force","4",{"title":6,"description":723},false,"en\u002FGit\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force",[721,733],"Team Collaboration",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F","jT0Bc-_BtBWAPiLLhA2-J25gs5k1j771cxEV-F16usI",{"newer":738,"older":742},{"url":739,"title":740,"date":741},"\u002Fen\u002Fai\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F03\u002Fgemini-gems-tutorial-build-your-own-ai-assistant\u002F","Gemini Gems Tutorial: Easily Build Your Own AI Assistant","2026-03-03 16:34:17",{"url":743,"title":744,"date":745},"\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F22\u002Fmacos-time-machine-speed-up-with-node-modules-exclusion\u002F","macOS Time Machine Taking Forever? One Trick to Speed It Up","2026-02-22 11:30:22",[747,752,757],{"url":748,"title":749,"date":750,"readingMinutes":751},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fgit-default-branch-master-to-main\u002F","Git init Shows a master Branch Hint? Here's How to Set main as Default","2026-01-22 16:20:40","3",{"url":753,"title":754,"date":755,"readingMinutes":756},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F21\u002Fgit-worktree-multiple-ai-agents-one-project\u002F","What Is Git Worktree? The Secret to Running Multiple AI Agents in One Project","2026-01-21 16:04:27","5",{"url":758,"title":759,"date":760,"readingMinutes":751},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2024\u002F12\u002F20\u002Fnew-git-commands-you-should-try\u002F","New Git Commands You Should Start Using","2024-12-20 23:30:28",1784020351374]